Scientists have found a way to detect related stars.
Astrophysics from the University of California in Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
The discovery of specialists is expected to make it possible to search for relatives among the stars, i.e. from one cluster.
The results of their studies were published in Nature magazine and are available briefly on the University's website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearest stars is turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas prior to the formation of the stars.
Even if a born star then leaves the star cluster, the chemical composition of the star can determine its birthplace and the region of birth.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
Simulation results from astrophysics show that such differences should not occur.
In their research, experts modelled two interstellar gas streams that together formed a cloud.
This object, for several million years under its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added tags to the initial gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieved a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
Astrophysics believe that their research proves that it is possible to search for chemically related stars and to identify possible regions of formation of such objects.
