Recalling the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights.
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis proposed a bill under which trade union organization is protected as civil law.
"Where trade unions are, there are middle-class jobs," says Allison, the Minnesota Democrat, who is the co-chair of the Progressive Fracture Congress.
That's why I'm proud to introduce the Employee Empowerment Act along with the symbol of the John Lewis Civil Rights Movement.
This innovative bill will provide workers with the same legal opportunities to discriminate against trade union organizations as other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of trade union opponents
Amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act to allow workers who face discrimination for participating in trade union organizations to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and fines - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative — at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Allison, Lewis and the drafters are proposing is to remember a very American idea.
Despite the attacks on trade unions in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states throughout the country — Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labour rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when that country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his associates helped the country to adopt a constitution designed to guarantee that Hideki Todjo’s paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in shaping a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the workers' right to organize, to negotiate and to act collectively is guaranteed”.
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his associates helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new State, the Germans included an article that openly stated: “The right to form associations to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to everyone and to every profession or activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will not have legal effect; measures to that end will be considered illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, which will be adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to defend their interests”.
In generations, Americans have accepted as due a basic provision that labour rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and to participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government institutions - should be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago,
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the forces of the nation, but has increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it should be for us.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the expansion of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - was long overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis are reviving ideals that historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge is temporarily blocking a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the U.S., a federal judge temporarily blocked the enactment of the Louisiana Act on Sunday, about which his supporters say that he is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
According to this measure, which was signed by the Governor of Louisiana, Bobby Ginadl, in June, and was to enter into force on 1 September, doctors who perform abortions would have been required to receive patients in the hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge ' s decision meant that doctors could continue to perform legal abortions for the time being by continuing to seek such authority.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to exercise authority," wrote Judge John de Gravells in his judgement.
The hearing will be scheduled within the month at which the judge will render a more permanent ruling on the law.
Advocates of the right to abortion were happy to meet this decision, the last in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authority.
“Today's decision guarantees that the women of Louisiana will be protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights”, said Nancy Northap, President and Head of the Centre for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit against the law on behalf of three out of five state clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who did not file a complaint in the case and also applied for admission.
Louisiana is part of the 11 states that have enacted such laws, and the courts have recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
The key parts of the Texas law, which would close most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by the federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion, along with the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that admissions laws impose medical restrictions that are not necessary in medical terms.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures were aimed at protecting women ' s health, although some also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has the power to receive a hospital, informed the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all the other doctors in the state were to stop doing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would have stopped doing it, the group reported.
Criticizing that decision, Louisiana officials said that they would not punish abortion doctors while their applications for admission were pending.
