In addition, Wanda owns the American AMC Entertainment Holdings cinema network, making the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda is planning to equip all its shopping centres, hotels and entertainment places with e-commerce services, which will be developed by the newly created rival Alibaba.
According to Dong Tze, who will lead the new company, Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million to 100 million by next year.
The new site should be the world's largest platform online-to-offline, notes Dong Cet.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) is to attract customers on the Internet to go to regular offline shops or to buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is the sale of coupons such as Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the largest "bird" in online commerce," said Van Jianglin, head of Wanda (Bloomberg quote).
"Now there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation everyone's chances are roughly equal," he says.
China's Internet market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates that it will increase to $395 billion more than three times by 2015 compared to 2011.
The number of Chinese Internet users has increased to 632 million, bringing official statistics to Bloomberg: this is more than the population of any country in the world except India.
And it is projected that by 2015, this number could increase to 850 million.
Union of the Rich
The head of Tencent Ma Huaten was until recently the richest man in China, but according to the Bloomberg millionaire index, the founder of Alibaba, Jack Ma, has already surpassed it by $5.5 billion.
