Israeli children return to school after the Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in the territories near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters when rockets and mines rained on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed while the Territory was recovering from fighting.
The beginning of school was a source of joy and excitement to the rocket-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern town of Ashdod, the Pashos kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed traces of fragments from the walls and rollers before the students arrived.
"We're a little afraid, but we're happy to look into the future," said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to get back to a normal life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said that suddenly she started going back to school "a little weird."
"It was a difficult time, and we didn't leave our homes at all," she said.
President Reven Rivlin visited Kibbutz, located near the Gaza border, to express his support.
Before the ceasefire stopped the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements, such as Saad, did not enter the streets or left their homes, leaving the Gaza Strip for safer areas to escape from rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, settlements near the Gaza border, where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mine, doubt that they should return.
The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families had not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools for that time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the border with Gaza, which had made a great effort from Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study carefully and said, "We will do our best to give you knowledge and to ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately put an end to the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as the Hamas demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade on Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its weapons and return the bodies of the two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of proximity talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians were killed in the war, three quarters of whom were civilians, and at least 494 children, as estimated by the Palestinian side and the United Nations.
Israel contests these figures and contends that at least half of those killed were militants; however, it did not provide substantial evidence to support this claim.
Sixty-six soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed on the Israeli side.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gazan militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
In the meantime, the Israeli army carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
As a result of Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip had been damaged and destroyed, and it was estimated that 250,000 people had taken refuge in more than 100 schools, which had been converted into shelters.
Because tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and fighting continued, education officials postponed the beginning of the school year last week.
"I hope the school will soon open so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children," said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a school in Gaza.
