The tax burden on the entrepreneurs of the Washington Zone is increasing as the economy recovers
The recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax accounts for companies across the country increased moderately last year, when economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington area were no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia all paid $27.6 billion to state and local treasury in fiscal year 2013, an increase of 3.8 per cent over the $22.6 billion collected for 2012.
The tax burden on state and local business increased by 4.3 per cent last year, to $671 billion, compared to 3.9 per cent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after the years after each other, when the accounts fell, in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes increased faster, 4.3 per cent than local taxes, 3.9 per cent, according to a study conducted by a professional service firm, Ernst & Young and the State Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the tax revenue in the district, 56 per cent, comes from taxes on entrepreneurs, while 36 per cent of Maryland tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 per cent, generates the lowest tax revenues, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenues is due to the return of company real estate value, according to researchers, which raised real estate taxes by 3.7 per cent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 per cent.
While large states, such as California, New York and Texas, account for a large share of these revenues, the same seems to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia together paid $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, an increase of $9.6 billion over 2012 - a 4.2 per cent increase over the previous year.
However, the observed return of real estate value has no similar effect on the growth of state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one fifth of company tax accounts.
Virginia and D.C. companies pay about half of the state and local tax accounts in the form of real estate taxes.
"What happens in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around D.C., belongs either to the government or to a non-profit organization that does not pay property taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, Executive Director of the State Tax Center.
Thus, Maryland has to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that are available in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the re-establishment of the real estate market.
Business income also seems to be improving, according to these data.
Companies in the region have declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, an increase of $2.1 billion over 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion of corporate income tax revenue, most of it in the region.
Although trends are in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level does not increase at the same rate in all three locations.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was the same as the national average, 4.3 per cent, while the growth rate in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 per cent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average of 4.1 per cent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) of 6 per cent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 per cent, while in the district it is relatively high at 9.975 per cent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year revealed that Virginia has lower taxes on state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favourable climate for taxes on entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from her neighbour from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a law reducing the corporate rate from 6.9 per cent to 6 per cent this year, as in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 per cent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, this law could raise the income tax rate for entrepreneurs even to 3 per cent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small business in the Washington area seems to be feeling better and thus paying more taxes on the state and local level, according to a recent study.
Taxes on entrepreneurs paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners - the transition structure that most small firms operate - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia grew by 20 per cent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher rate of growth than taxes on entrepreneurs as a whole.
Researchers say that the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country are likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments rising by 6.2 per cent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind, as lower federal spending affects the labour market in the region.
