A law whose entry into force is rushed by parliamentarians obliges Russians to keep their personal data on the Internet in the territory of the Russian Federation.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, store, store, refine and retrieve the personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located in Russian territory, as well as to indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law empowers Roskomnadzor to restrict access to information processed in violation of the Russian legislation on personal data by a court decision.
The Act also proposes the establishment of so-called “black lists” of offending websites, an automated information system entitled “List of violators of the rights of personal data subjects”.
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The draft law was authored by Andrei Lugova and Vadim Polin of LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko of KDPF.
Money and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent.
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first head of the Douma Information Policy Committee, Leonid Levin, stated that he saw no problem in moving the date of entry into force of the Personal Data Protection Act.
According to him, those companies that would not have their own storage facilities for Russians in the territory of the Russian Federation by 1 January 2015 would be able to rent them, for example, to Rostelecoma, who had repeatedly said that they were willing to rent their servers and were already providing their servers, to Mail Group, Western companies that were already providing their servers.
"There are also several independent data centres willing to cooperate in this field," he added.
“If companies decide to comply with the law and continue working in the territory of the Russian Federation, there is no problem - they will receive technological accommodation”, said Levin.
Disputing Bill
