Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of the human being.
An angry expression is biologically universal for mankind, and every organ and group of muscles involved in its creation is not random, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, researchers in Australia and the United States have discovered.
Their discoveries were reported in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and can be summarized in a press release from the University of California in Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - the swollen and lowered eyebrows, stretched into a thin line of lips, the swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and makes it even blind children who have never seen it, notes the lead author, Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists discovered that this emotion arose to effectively manage disputes during the conflict.
The more physical damage one person can do to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his condition, and he communicates it to the person concerned by means of anger.
Researchers have also found another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and to be manipulative, to be free to impose conditions that are not beneficial to them, and to prefer forceful methods of conflict resolution to be peaceful.
Rejecting from the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining,” scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry face should represent an angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force him to accept its terms as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, researchers modelled on the computer individuals who had or did not have each of the seven elements of the angry person and showed them to informers.
Although the lower eyebrows or the forward chin alone did not make the face angry, the stronger physical personality was accepted by the researchers.
Like animals, man’s anger expresses a threat: an exaggerated display of his own power, forcing him to accept and submit.
A person blows up his nostrils and his lips for the same purpose as a frog that blows up, or a baboon that shows his fangs.
“Anger” is “started” by the respondent's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that best demonstrates the consequences of this refusal to the contrary.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry person is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” noted anthropologist John Tuby.
The minicom offered 250 million rubles to Crimea's radio company.
In 2014, 250 million rubles were proposed from the federal budget for the autonomous non-profit organization Crimea Teleradio Company.
This is stated in a draft Government decree prepared by the department that was consulted by Lenta.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the project, the federal budget grants will be allocated “to cover the costs of creating the conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment”.
In particular, it is intended to convert the hardware and studio unit, the video walls, the central hardware room and the video server.
A mobile television station and a satellite transmitter are also planned.
In addition, from the funds allocated, the company will pay for the use of the fibre-optic line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget provided for the Minicom.
The State Broadcasting Company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, television coverage of the television broadcasting company is more than 75 per cent of the peninsula.
In 2011, Crimea's Teleradio Company was licensed to broadcast digital television.
